<p><b>Haskell</b> (<span class="rt-commentedText nowrap"><span class="IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang="en-fonipa"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title="Help:IPA/English">/<span style="border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title="/ˈ/: primary stress follows">ˈ</span><span title="'h' in 'hi'">h</span><span title="/æ/: 'a' in 'bad'">æ</span><span title="'s' in 'sigh'">s</span><span title="'k' in 'kind'">k</span><span title="/əl/: 'le' in 'bottle'">əl</span></span>/</a></span></span><sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>) is a <a href="/wiki/General-purpose_programming_language" title="General-purpose programming language">general-purpose</a>, <a href="/wiki/Static_typing" class="mw-redirect" title="Static typing">statically typed</a>, <a href="/wiki/Purely_functional_programming" title="Purely functional programming">purely functional</a> <a href="/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language">programming language</a> with <a href="/wiki/Type_inference" title="Type inference">type inference</a> and <a href="/wiki/Lazy_evaluation" title="Lazy evaluation">lazy evaluation</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003-27"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Haskell pioneered several programming language <a href="#Features">features</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Type_class" title="Type class">type classes</a>, which enable <a href="/wiki/Type_safety" title="Type safety">type-safe</a> <a href="/wiki/Operator_overloading" title="Operator overloading">operator overloading</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Monad_(functional_programming)" title="Monad (functional programming)">monadic</a> <a href="/wiki/Input/output" title="Input/output">input/output</a> (IO). It is named after <a href="/wiki/Logic" title="Logic">logician</a> <a href="/wiki/Haskell_Curry" title="Haskell Curry">Haskell Curry</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHudakHughesPeyton_JonesWadler2007_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHudakHughesPeyton_JonesWadler2007-1"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Haskell's main implementation is the <a href="/wiki/Glasgow_Haskell_Compiler" title="Glasgow Haskell Compiler">Glasgow Haskell Compiler</a> (GHC).
</p><p>Haskell's <a href="/wiki/Semantics_(computer_science)" title="Semantics (computer science)">semantics</a> are historically based on those of the <a href="/wiki/Miranda_(programming_language)" title="Miranda (programming language)">Miranda</a> programming language, which served to focus the efforts of the initial Haskell working group.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The last formal specification of the language was made in July 2010, while the development of GHC continues to expand Haskell via language extensions.
</p><p>Haskell is used in academia and industry.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As of May&nbsp;2021<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, Haskell was the 28th most popular programming language by <a href="/wiki/Google_search" class="mw-redirect" title="Google search">Google searches</a> for tutorials,<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and made up less than 1% of active users on the <a href="/wiki/GitHub" title="GitHub">GitHub</a> source code repository.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="History">History</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>After the release of <a href="/wiki/Miranda_(programming_language)" title="Miranda (programming language)">Miranda</a> by Research Software Ltd. in 1985, interest in lazy functional languages grew. By 1987, more than a dozen non-<a href="/wiki/Strict_function" title="Strict function">strict</a>, purely functional programming languages existed. Miranda was the most widely used, but it was <a href="/wiki/Proprietary_software" title="Proprietary software">proprietary software</a>. At the conference on <a href="/wiki/Functional_Programming_Languages_and_Computer_Architecture" class="mw-redirect" title="Functional Programming Languages and Computer Architecture">Functional Programming Languages and Computer Architecture</a> (FPCA '87) in <a href="/wiki/Portland,_Oregon" title="Portland, Oregon">Portland, Oregon</a>, there was a strong consensus that a committee be formed to define an <a href="/wiki/Open_standard" title="Open standard">open standard</a> for such languages. The committee's purpose was to consolidate existing <a href="/wiki/Functional_languages" class="mw-redirect" title="Functional languages">functional languages</a> into a common one to serve as a basis for future research in functional-language design.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003Preface_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003Preface-34"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Haskell_1.0_to_1.4">Haskell 1.0 to 1.4</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Haskell 1.0 to 1.4"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Haskell was developed by a committee, attempting to bring together off the shelf solutions where possible.
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Type_classes" class="mw-redirect" title="Type classes">Type classes</a>, which enable <a href="/wiki/Type_safety" title="Type safety">type-safe</a> <a href="/wiki/Operator_overloading" title="Operator overloading">operator overloading</a>, were first proposed by <a href="/wiki/Philip_Wadler" title="Philip Wadler">Philip Wadler</a> and Stephen Blott to address the ad-hoc handling of equality types and arithmetic overloading in languages at the time.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In early versions of Haskell up until and including version 1.2, user interaction and <a href="/wiki/Input/output" title="Input/output">input/output</a> (IO) were handled by both streams based and continuation based mechanisms which were widely considered unsatisfactory.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In version 1.3, <a href="/wiki/Monad_(functional_programming)" title="Monad (functional programming)">monadic</a> IO was introduced, along with the generalisation of type classes to higher kinds (type constructors). Along with "do notation", which provides syntactic sugar for the Monad type class, this gave Haskell an effect system that maintained referential transparency and was convenient.
</p><p>Other notable changes in early versions were the approach to the 'seq' function, which creates a data dependency between values, and is used in lazy languages to avoid excessive memory consumption; with it moving from a type class to a standard function to make refactoring more practical.
</p><p>The first version of Haskell ("Haskell 1.0") was defined in 1990.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHudakHughesPeyton_JonesWadler2007_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHudakHughesPeyton_JonesWadler2007-1"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The committee's efforts resulted in a series of language definitions (1.0, 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, 1.4).
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Base-classes.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Base-classes.svg/250px-Base-classes.svg.png" decoding="async" width="250" height="325" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Base-classes.svg/500px-Base-classes.svg.png 1.5x" data-file-width="510" data-file-height="663"></a><figcaption>Hierarchy of <a href="/wiki/Type_class" title="Type class">type classes</a> in the Haskell prelude as of GHC 7.10. The inclusion of Foldable and Traversable (with corresponding changes to the type signatures of some functions), and of Applicative as intermediate between Functor and Monad, are deviations from the Haskell 2010 standard.</figcaption></figure>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Haskell_98">Haskell 98</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Haskell 98"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In late 1997, the series culminated in <i>Haskell 98</i>, intended to specify a stable, minimal, portable version of the language and an accompanying standard <a href="/wiki/Library_(computer_science)" class="mw-redirect" title="Library (computer science)">library</a> for teaching, and as a base for future extensions. The committee expressly welcomed creating extensions and variants of Haskell 98 via adding and incorporating experimental features.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003Preface_34-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003Preface-34"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In February 1999, the Haskell 98 language standard was originally published as <i>The Haskell 98 Report</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003Preface_34-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003Preface-34"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In January 2003, a revised version was published as <i>Haskell 98 Language and Libraries: The Revised Report</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003_27-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003-27"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The language continues to evolve rapidly, with the <a href="/wiki/Glasgow_Haskell_Compiler" title="Glasgow Haskell Compiler">Glasgow Haskell Compiler</a> (GHC) implementation representing the current <i>de facto</i> standard.<sup id="cite_ref-HaskellWikiImpl_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-HaskellWikiImpl-37"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Haskell_2010">Haskell 2010</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Haskell 2010"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In early 2006, the process of defining a successor to the Haskell 98 standard, informally named <i>Haskell Prime</i>, began.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This was intended to be an ongoing incremental process to revise the language definition, producing a new revision up to once per year. The first revision, named <i>Haskell 2010</i>, was announced in November 2009<sup id="cite_ref-2010ann_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2010ann-2"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and published in July 2010.
</p><p>Haskell 2010 is an incremental update to the language, mostly incorporating several well-used and uncontroversial features previously enabled via compiler-specific flags.
</p>
<ul><li>Hierarchical module names. Module names are allowed to consist of dot-separated sequences of capitalized identifiers, rather than only one such identifier. This lets modules be named in a hierarchical manner (e.g., <code>Data.List</code> instead of <code>List</code>), although technically modules are still in a single monolithic namespace. This extension was specified in an addendum to Haskell 98 and was in practice universally used.</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Foreign_function_interface" title="Foreign function interface">foreign function interface</a> (FFI) allows bindings to other programming languages. Only bindings to <a href="/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title="C (programming language)">C</a> are specified in the Report, but the design allows for other language bindings. To support this, data type declarations were permitted to contain no constructors, enabling robust nonce types for foreign data that could not be constructed in Haskell. This extension was also previously specified in an Addendum to the Haskell 98 Report and widely used.</li>
<li>So-called <i>n</i>+<i>k</i> patterns (definitions of the form <code>fact (n+1) = (n+1) * fact n</code>) were no longer allowed. This <a href="/wiki/Syntactic_sugar" title="Syntactic sugar">syntactic sugar</a> had misleading semantics, in which the code looked like it used the <code>(+)</code> operator, but in fact desugared to code using <code>(-)</code> and <code>(&gt;=)</code>.</li>
<li>The rules of <a href="/wiki/Type_inference" title="Type inference">type inference</a> were relaxed to allow more programs to type check.</li>
<li>Some <a href="/wiki/Syntax_(programming_languages)" title="Syntax (programming languages)">syntax</a> issues (changes in the formal grammar) were fixed: <a href="/wiki/Pattern_guard" class="mw-redirect" title="Pattern guard">pattern guards</a> were added, allowing pattern matching within guards; resolution of <a href="/wiki/Order_of_operations" title="Order of operations">operator fixity</a> was specified in a simpler way that reflected actual practice; an edge case in the interaction of the language's <a href="/wiki/Lexical_syntax" class="mw-redirect" title="Lexical syntax">lexical syntax</a> of operators and comments was addressed, and the interaction of do-notation and if-then-else was tweaked to eliminate unexpected syntax errors.</li>
<li>The <code>LANGUAGE</code> <a href="/wiki/Directive_(programming)" title="Directive (programming)">pragma</a> was specified. By 2010, dozens of extensions to the language were in wide use, and GHC (among other compilers) provided the <code>LANGUAGE</code> pragma to specify individual extensions with a list of identifiers. Haskell 2010 compilers are required to support the <code>Haskell2010</code> extension and are encouraged to support several others, which correspond to extensions added in Haskell 2010.</li></ul>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Future_standards">Future standards</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Future standards"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The next formal specification had been planned for 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-2020committee_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2020committee-3"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On 29 October 2021, with GHC version 9.2.1, the GHC2021 extension was released. While this is not a formal language spec, it combines several stable, widely-used GHC extensions to Haskell 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-ghc9,2,1_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ghc9,2,1-39"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Features">Features</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Features"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1236090951"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Haskell_features" title="Haskell features">Haskell features</a></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1236090951"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Glasgow_Haskell_Compiler#Extensions_to_Haskell" title="Glasgow Haskell Compiler">Glasgow Haskell Compiler §&nbsp;Extensions to Haskell</a></div>
<p>Haskell features <a href="/wiki/Lazy_evaluation" title="Lazy evaluation">lazy evaluation</a>, <a href="/wiki/Anonymous_function" title="Anonymous function">lambda expressions</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pattern_matching" title="Pattern matching">pattern matching</a>, <a href="/wiki/List_comprehension" title="List comprehension">list comprehension</a>, <a href="/wiki/Type_class" title="Type class">type classes</a> and <a href="/wiki/Type_polymorphism" class="mw-redirect" title="Type polymorphism">type polymorphism</a>. It is a <a href="/wiki/Purely_functional_programming" title="Purely functional programming">purely functional programming</a> language, which means that functions generally have no <a href="/wiki/Side_effect_(computer_science)" title="Side effect (computer science)">side effects</a>. A distinct construct exists to represent side effects, <a href="/wiki/Orthogonal#Computer_science" class="mw-redirect" title="Orthogonal">orthogonal</a> to the type of functions. A pure function can return a side effect that is subsequently executed, modeling the <a href="/wiki/Pure_function#Impure_functions" title="Pure function">impure functions</a> of other languages.
</p><p>Haskell has a <a href="/wiki/Strong_and_weak_typing" title="Strong and weak typing">strong</a>, <a href="/wiki/Static_type#Static_typing" class="mw-redirect" title="Static type">static</a> type system based on <a href="/wiki/Hindley%E2%80%93Milner_type_inference" class="mw-redirect" title="Hindley–Milner type inference">Hindley–Milner type inference</a>. Its principal innovation in this area is type classes, originally conceived as a principled way to add <a href="/wiki/Polymorphism_(computer_science)" title="Polymorphism (computer science)">overloading</a> to the language,<sup id="cite_ref-wadler89_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wadler89-41"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but since finding many more uses.<sup id="cite_ref-hallgren01_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hallgren01-42"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The construct that represents side effects is an example of a <a href="/wiki/Monad_(functional_programming)" title="Monad (functional programming)">monad</a>: a general framework which can model various computations such as error handling, <a href="/wiki/Nondeterministic_algorithm" title="Nondeterministic algorithm">nondeterminism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Parsing" title="Parsing">parsing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Software_transactional_memory" title="Software transactional memory">software transactional memory</a>. They are defined as ordinary datatypes, but Haskell provides some <a href="/wiki/Syntactic_sugar" title="Syntactic sugar">syntactic sugar</a> for their use.
</p><p>Haskell has an open, published specification,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003_27-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPeyton_Jones2003-27"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href="#Implementations">multiple implementations exist</a>. Its main implementation, the <a href="/wiki/Glasgow_Haskell_Compiler" title="Glasgow Haskell Compiler">Glasgow Haskell Compiler</a> (GHC), is both an <a href="/wiki/Interpreter_(computing)" title="Interpreter (computing)">interpreter</a> and <a href="/wiki/Machine_code" title="Machine code">native-code</a> <a href="/wiki/Compiler" title="Compiler">compiler</a> that runs on most platforms. GHC is noted for its rich type system incorporating recent innovations such as <a href="/wiki/Generalized_algebraic_data_type" title="Generalized algebraic data type">generalized algebraic data types</a> and type families. <a href="/wiki/The_Computer_Language_Benchmarks_Game" title="The Computer Language Benchmarks Game">The Computer Language Benchmarks Game</a> also highlights its high-performance implementation of <a href="/wiki/Concurrency_(computer_science)" title="Concurrency (computer science)">concurrency</a> and <a href="/wiki/Parallel_computing" title="Parallel computing">parallelism</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-shootout_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-shootout-43"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An active, growing community exists around the language, and more than 5,400 third-party open-source libraries and tools are available in the online package repository <i>Hackage</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-hackage-stats_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hackage-stats-44"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Code_examples">Code examples</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Code examples"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1236090951"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Haskell_features#Examples" title="Haskell features">Haskell features §&nbsp;Examples</a></div>
<p>A <a href="/wiki/%22Hello,_World!%22_program" title="&quot;Hello, World!&quot; program">"Hello, World!" program</a> in Haskell (only the last line is strictly necessary):
</p>
<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-haskell mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="kr">module</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nn">Main</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nf">main</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kr">where</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="c1">-- not needed in interpreter, is the default in a module file</span>

<span class="nf">main</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">::</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">IO</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nb">()</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="c1">-- the compiler can infer this type definition</span>
<span class="nf">main</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">putStrLn</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="s">"Hello, World!"</span>
</pre></div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Factorial" title="Factorial">factorial</a> function in Haskell, defined in a few different ways (the first line is the <a href="/wiki/Type_signature" title="Type signature">type annotation</a>, which is optional and is the same for each implementation):
</p>
<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-haskell mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">::</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="kt">Integral</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">a</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">a</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">a</span>

<span class="c1">-- Using recursion (with the "ifthenelse" expression)</span>
<span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kr">if</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">2</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="kr">then</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="kr">else</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">*</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1">-- Using recursion (with pattern matching)</span>
<span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span>
<span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">*</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1">-- Using recursion (with guards)</span>
<span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">otherwise</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">*</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1">-- Using a list and the "product" function</span>
<span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">product</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="o">..</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1">-- Using fold (implements "product")</span>
<span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">n</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">foldl</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="o">..</span><span class="n">n</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1">-- Point-free style</span>
<span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">foldr</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">.</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">enumFromTo</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span>
</pre></div>
<p>Using Haskell's <a href="/wiki/Fixed-point_combinator" title="Fixed-point combinator">Fixed-point combinator</a> allows this function to be written without any explicit recursion.
</p>
<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-haskell mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="kr">import</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="nn">Data.Function</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nf">fix</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="nf">factorial</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">fix</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">fac</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="kr">where</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">fac</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">f</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">x</span><span class="w"> </span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">x</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">otherwise</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">x</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">*</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">f</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">-</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
<p><br>
As the <i>Integer</i> type has <a href="/wiki/Arbitrary-precision" class="mw-redirect" title="Arbitrary-precision">arbitrary-precision</a>, this code will compute values such as <code>factorial 100000</code> (a 456,574-digit number), with no loss of precision.
</p><p>An implementation of an algorithm similar to <a href="/wiki/Quick_sort" class="mw-redirect" title="Quick sort">quick sort</a> over lists, where the first element is taken as the pivot:
</p>
<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-haskell mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="c1">-- Type annotation (optional, same for each implementation)</span>
<span class="nf">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">::</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">Ord</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">a</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">a</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">-&gt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">a</span><span class="p">]</span>

<span class="c1">-- Using list comprehensions</span>
<span class="nf">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">[]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">[]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="c1">-- The empty list is already sorted</span>
<span class="nf">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="kt">:</span><span class="n">xs</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">a</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">a</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">&lt;-</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">xs</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">a</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="c1">-- Sort the left part of the list</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="o">++</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">++</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="c1">-- Insert pivot between two sorted parts</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="n">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">a</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">|</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">a</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">&lt;-</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">xs</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">a</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">&gt;=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="c1">-- Sort the right part of the list</span>

<span class="c1">-- Using filter</span>
<span class="nf">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">[]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="kt">[]</span>
<span class="nf">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="kt">:</span><span class="n">xs</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="ow">=</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">filter</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&lt;</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">xs</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="o">++</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">++</span>
<span class="w"> </span><span class="n">quickSort</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">filter</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">&gt;=</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="n">xs</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Implementations">Implementations</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Implementations"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>All listed implementations are distributed under <a href="/wiki/Open_source_license" class="mw-redirect" title="Open source license">open source licenses</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-implementations_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-implementations-45"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Implementations that fully or nearly comply with the Haskell 98 standard include:
</p>
<ul><li>The <a href="/wiki/Glasgow_Haskell_Compiler" title="Glasgow Haskell Compiler">Glasgow Haskell Compiler</a> (GHC) compiles to native code on many different processor architectures, and to <a href="/wiki/ANSI_C" title="ANSI C">ANSI C</a>, via one of two <a href="/wiki/Intermediate_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Intermediate language">intermediate languages</a>: <a href="/wiki/C--" title="C--">C--</a>, or in more recent versions, <a href="/wiki/LLVM" title="LLVM">LLVM</a> (formerly Low Level Virtual Machine) bitcode.<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> GHC has become the <i>de facto</i> standard Haskell dialect.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There are libraries (e.g., bindings to <a href="/wiki/OpenGL" title="OpenGL">OpenGL</a>) that work only with GHC. GHC was also distributed with the <a href="/wiki/Haskell_platform" class="mw-redirect" title="Haskell platform">Haskell platform</a>. GHC features an asynchronous runtime that also schedules threads across multiple CPU cores similar to <a href="/wiki/Go_(programming_language)" title="Go (programming language)">the Go runtime</a>.</li>
<li>Jhc, a Haskell compiler written by John Meacham, emphasizes speed and efficiency of generated programs and exploring new program transformations.
<ul><li>Ajhc is a fork of Jhc.</li></ul></li>
<li>The Utrecht Haskell Compiler (UHC) is a Haskell implementation from <a href="/wiki/Utrecht_University" title="Utrecht University">Utrecht University</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It supports almost all Haskell 98 features plus many experimental extensions. It is implemented using <a href="/wiki/Attribute_grammar" title="Attribute grammar">attribute grammars</a> and is primarily used for research on generated type systems and language extensions.</li></ul>
<p>Implementations no longer actively maintained include:
</p>
<ul><li>The Haskell User's Gofer System (<a href="/wiki/Hugs_(interpreter)" title="Hugs (interpreter)">Hugs</a>) is a <a href="/wiki/Bytecode" title="Bytecode">bytecode</a> interpreter. It was once one of the implementations used most widely, alongside the GHC compiler,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHudakHughesPeyton_JonesWadler200712–22_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHudakHughesPeyton_JonesWadler200712–22-50"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but has now been mostly replaced by GHCi. It also comes with a graphics library.</li>
<li>HBC is an early implementation supporting Haskell 1.4. It was implemented by <a href="/wiki/Lennart_Augustsson" title="Lennart Augustsson">Lennart Augustsson</a> in, and based on, <a href="/wiki/Lazy_ML" class="mw-redirect" title="Lazy ML">Lazy ML</a>. It has not been actively developed for some time.</li>
<li>nhc98 is a bytecode compiler focusing on minimizing memory use.
<ul><li>The York Haskell Compiler (<a href="/wiki/Yhc" title="Yhc">Yhc</a>) was a fork of nhc98, with the goals of being simpler, more portable and efficient, and integrating support for Hat, the Haskell tracer. It also had a <a href="/wiki/JavaScript" title="JavaScript">JavaScript</a> backend, allowing users to run Haskell programs in <a href="/wiki/Web_browser" title="Web browser">web browsers</a>.</li></ul></li></ul>
<p>Implementations not fully Haskell 98 compliant, and using a variant Haskell language, include:
</p>
<ul><li>Eta and Frege are dialects of Haskell targeting the <a href="/wiki/Java_virtual_machine" title="Java virtual machine">Java virtual machine</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Gofer_(software)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gofer (software)">Gofer</a> is an educational dialect of Haskell, with a feature called <i>constructor classes</i>, developed by Mark Jones. It is supplanted by Haskell User's Gofer System (Hugs).</li>
<li>Helium, a newer dialect of Haskell. The focus is on making learning easier via clearer error messages by disabling type classes as a default.</li></ul>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Notable_applications">Notable applications</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Notable applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Agda_(programming_language)" title="Agda (programming language)">Agda</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Proof_assistant" title="Proof assistant">proof assistant</a> written in Haskell.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cabal_(software)" title="Cabal (software)">Cabal</a> is a tool for <a href="/wiki/Build_automation" title="Build automation">building</a> and packaging Haskell libraries and programs.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Darcs" title="Darcs">Darcs</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Revision_control_system" class="mw-redirect" title="Revision control system">revision control system</a> written in Haskell, with several innovative features, such as more precise control of patches to apply.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Glasgow_Haskell_Compiler" title="Glasgow Haskell Compiler">Glasgow Haskell Compiler</a> (GHC) is also often a testbed for advanced functional programming features and optimizations in other programming languages.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Git-annex" title="Git-annex">Git-annex</a> is a tool to manage (big) data files under <a href="/wiki/Git" title="Git">Git</a> version control. It also provides a distributed file synchronization system (git-annex assistant).</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Linspire" title="Linspire">Linspire</a> Linux chose Haskell for system tools development.<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pandoc" title="Pandoc">Pandoc</a> is a tool to convert one markup format into another.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Pugs_(compiler)" title="Pugs (compiler)">Pugs</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Compiler" title="Compiler">compiler</a> and <a href="/wiki/Interpreter_(computing)" title="Interpreter (computing)">interpreter</a> for the <a href="/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language">programming language</a> then named <a href="/wiki/Perl" title="Perl">Perl</a> 6, but since renamed <a href="/wiki/Raku_(programming_language)" title="Raku (programming language)">Raku</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/TidalCycles" title="TidalCycles">TidalCycles</a> is a domain special language for live coding musical patterns, embedded in Haskell.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Xmonad" title="Xmonad">Xmonad</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Window_manager" title="Window manager">window manager</a> for the <a href="/wiki/X_Window_System" title="X Window System">X Window System</a>, written fully in Haskell.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>GarganText<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is a collaborative tool to map through semantic analysis texts on any <a href="/wiki/Web_browser" title="Web browser">web browser</a>, written fully in Haskell and <a href="/wiki/PureScript" title="PureScript">PureScript</a>, which is used for instance in the research community to draw up state-of-the-art reports and roadmaps.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Industry">Industry</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Industry"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Bluespec" title="Bluespec">Bluespec</a> <a href="/wiki/SystemVerilog" title="SystemVerilog">SystemVerilog</a> (BSV) is a language extension of Haskell, for designing <a href="/wiki/Electronics" title="Electronics">electronics</a>. It is an example of a <a href="/wiki/Domain-specific_language" title="Domain-specific language">domain-specific language</a> embedded into Haskell. Further, Bluespec, Inc.'s tools are implemented in Haskell.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cryptol" title="Cryptol">Cryptol</a>, a language and toolchain for developing and verifying <a href="/wiki/Cryptography" title="Cryptography">cryptography</a> algorithms, is implemented in Haskell.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Facebook" title="Facebook">Facebook</a> implements its anti-spam programs<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> in Haskell, maintaining the underlying data access library as <a href="/wiki/Open-source_software" title="Open-source software">open-source software</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Cardano_(blockchain_platform)" title="Cardano (blockchain platform)">Cardano blockchain platform</a> is implemented in Haskell.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/GitHub" title="GitHub">GitHub</a> implemented Semantic, an open-source library to analyze, diff, and interpret untrusted source code for many languages, in Haskell.<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Standard_Chartered" title="Standard Chartered">Standard Chartered</a>'s financial modelling language Mu is syntactic Haskell running on a strict runtime.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/SeL4" class="mw-redirect" title="SeL4">seL4</a>, the first <a href="/wiki/Formal_methods" title="Formal methods">formally verified</a> <a href="/wiki/Microkernel" title="Microkernel">microkernel</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-klein-sosp09_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-klein-sosp09-63"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> used Haskell as a prototyping language for the OS developer.<sup id="cite_ref-klein-sosp09_63-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-klein-sosp09-63"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference nowrap"><span title="Page / location: p.2">: p.2 </span></sup> At the same time, the Haskell code defined an executable specification with which to reason, for automatic translation by the theorem-proving tool.<sup id="cite_ref-klein-sosp09_63-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-klein-sosp09-63"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference nowrap"><span title="Page / location: p.3">: p.3 </span></sup> The Haskell code thus served as an intermediate prototype before final <a href="/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title="C (programming language)">C</a> refinement.<sup id="cite_ref-klein-sosp09_63-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-klein-sosp09-63"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class="reference nowrap"><span title="Page / location: p.3">: p.3 </span></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Target_Corporation" title="Target Corporation">Target</a> stores' supply chain optimization software is written in Haskell.<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Co%E2%80%93Star" title="Co–Star">Co–Star</a><sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mercury_Technologies" title="Mercury Technologies">Mercury Technologies</a>' back end is written in Haskell.<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Web">Web</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Web"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Notable <a href="/wiki/Web_framework" title="Web framework">web frameworks</a> written for Haskell include:<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>IHP</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Servant_(web_framework)" title="Servant (web framework)">Servant</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Snap_(web_framework)" title="Snap (web framework)">Snap</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Yesod_(web_framework)" title="Yesod (web framework)">Yesod</a></li></ul>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Criticism">Criticism</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Criticism"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Jan-Willem Maessen, in 2002, and <a href="/wiki/Simon_Peyton_Jones" title="Simon Peyton Jones">Simon Peyton Jones</a>, in 2003, discussed problems associated with lazy evaluation while also acknowledging the theoretical motives for it.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In addition to purely practical considerations such as improved performance,<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> they note that lazy evaluation makes it more difficult for programmers to reason about the performance of their code (particularly its space use).
</p><p>Bastiaan Heeren, Daan Leijen, and Arjan van IJzendoorn in 2003 also observed some stumbling blocks for Haskell learners: "The subtle syntax and sophisticated type system of Haskell are a double edged sword—highly appreciated by experienced programmers but also a source of frustration among beginners, since the generality of Haskell often leads to cryptic error messages."<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To address the error messages researchers from Utrecht University developed an advanced interpreter called Helium, which improved the user-friendliness of error messages by limiting the generality of some Haskell features. In particular it disables type classes by default.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Ben Lippmeier designed Disciple<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>73<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as a <a href="/wiki/Evaluation_strategy" title="Evaluation strategy">strict-by-default</a> (lazy by explicit annotation) dialect of Haskell with a type-and-effect system, to address Haskell's difficulties in reasoning about lazy evaluation and in using traditional data structures such as mutable arrays.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He argues (p. 20) that "destructive update furnishes the programmer with two important and powerful tools ... a set of efficient array-like data structures for managing collections of objects, and ... the ability to broadcast a new value to all parts of a program with minimal burden on the programmer."
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Robert_Harper_(computer_scientist)" title="Robert Harper (computer scientist)">Robert Harper</a>, one of the authors of Standard ML, has given his reasons for not using Haskell to teach introductory programming. Among these are the difficulty of reasoning about resource use with non-strict evaluation, that lazy evaluation complicates the definition of datatypes and inductive reasoning,<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the "inferiority" of Haskell's (old) class system compared to ML's module system.<sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Haskell's build tool, <a href="/wiki/Cabal_(software)" title="Cabal (software)">Cabal</a>, has historically been criticized for poorly handling multiple versions of the same library, a problem known as "Cabal hell". The Stackage server and <a href="/wiki/Stack_(Haskell)" title="Stack (Haskell)">Stack</a> build tool were made in response to these criticisms.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Cabal has since addressed this problem by borrowing ideas from a <a href="/wiki/Package_manager" title="Package manager">package manager</a> named <a href="/wiki/Nix_(package_manager)" title="Nix (package manager)">Nix</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> with the new approach becoming the default in 2019.
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Related_languages">Related languages</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Related languages"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href="/wiki/Clean_(programming_language)" title="Clean (programming language)">Clean</a> is a close, slightly older relative of Haskell. Its biggest deviation from Haskell is in the use of <a href="/wiki/Uniqueness_type" title="Uniqueness type">uniqueness types</a> instead of monads for <a href="/wiki/Input/output" title="Input/output">input/output</a> (I/O) and side effects.
</p><p>A series of languages inspired by Haskell, but with different type systems, have been developed, including:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Agda_(programming_language)" title="Agda (programming language)">Agda</a>, a functional language with <a href="/wiki/Dependent_type" title="Dependent type">dependent types</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Cayenne_(programming_language)" class="mw-redirect" title="Cayenne (programming language)">Cayenne</a>, with dependent types.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Elm_(programming_language)" title="Elm (programming language)">Elm</a>, a functional language to create web front-end apps, no support for user-defined or higher-<a href="/wiki/Kind_(type_theory)" title="Kind (type theory)">kinded</a> <a href="/wiki/Type_classes" class="mw-redirect" title="Type classes">type classes</a> or instances.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Epigram_(programming_language)" title="Epigram (programming language)">Epigram</a>, a functional language with dependent types suitable for proving properties of programs.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Idris_(programming_language)" title="Idris (programming language)">Idris</a>, a general purpose functional language with dependent types, developed at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_St_Andrews" title="University of St Andrews">University of St Andrews</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/PureScript" title="PureScript">PureScript</a> transpiles to JavaScript.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/%CE%A9mega" title="Ωmega">Ωmega</a>, a strict language that allows introduction of new <a href="/wiki/Kind_(type_theory)" title="Kind (type theory)">kinds</a>, and programming at the type level.</li></ul>
<p>Other related languages include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Curry_(programming_language)" title="Curry (programming language)">Curry</a>, a functional/logic programming language based on Haskell.</li></ul>
<p>Notable Haskell variants include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Generic_programming#Generic_Haskell" title="Generic programming">Generic Haskell</a>, a version of Haskell with type system support for <a href="/wiki/Generic_programming" title="Generic programming">generic programming</a>.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Hume_(programming_language)" title="Hume (programming language)">Hume</a>, a strict functional language for <a href="/wiki/Embedded_system" title="Embedded system">embedded systems</a> based on processes as stateless automata over a sort of tuples of one element mailbox channels where the state is kept by feedback into the mailboxes, and a mapping description from outputs to channels as box wiring, with a Haskell-like expression language and syntax.</li></ul>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Conferences_and_workshops">Conferences and workshops</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Haskell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Conferences and workshops"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Haskell community meets regularly for research and development activities. The main events are:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/International_Conference_on_Functional_Programming" title="International Conference on Functional Programming">International Conference on Functional Programming</a> (ICFP)</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Haskell_Symposium" class="mw-redirect" title="Haskell Symposium">Haskell Symposium</a> (formerly the Haskell Workshop)</li>
<li>Haskell Implementors Workshop</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Commercial_Users_of_Functional_Programming" class="mw-redirect" title="Commercial Users of Functional Programming">Commercial Users of Functional Programming</a> (CUFP)</li>
<li>ZuriHac,<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> kind of <a href="/wiki/Hackathon" title="Hackathon">Hackathon</a> held every year in <a href="/wiki/Zurich" title="Zurich">Zurich</a></li></ul>
<p>Starting in 2006, a series of organized <i>hackathons</i> has occurred, the Hac series, aimed at improving the programming language tools and libraries.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>

<li id="cite_note-klein-sosp09-63"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-klein-sosp09_63-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-klein-sosp09_63-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-klein-sosp09_63-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-klein-sosp09_63-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">
A formal proof of functional correctness was completed in 2009.
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1238218222"><cite id="CITEREFKleinElphinstoneHeiserAndronick2009" class="citation conference cs1">Klein, Gerwin; Elphinstone, Kevin; <a href="/wiki/Gernot_Heiser" title="Gernot Heiser">Heiser, Gernot</a>; Andronick, June; Cock, David; Derrin, Philip; Elkaduwe, Dhammika; Engelhardt, Kai; Kolanski, Rafal; Norrish, Michael; Sewell, Thomas; Tuch, Harvey; Winwood, Simon (October 2009). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.sigops.org/sosp/sosp09/papers/klein-sosp09.pdf">"seL4: Formal verification of an OS kernel"</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>. <i>22nd ACM Symposium on Operating System Principles</i>.
